  display: -ms-flexbox;

more than a year now and I've made a few rules for myself that I knew I should follow when building whoops: lightweight is key and smaller is easier to fly. However, with the release of the new Air75 and Air65, I was curious and wanted to see what the other end of the \"whoop spectrum\" was like. I thought to myself \"Is heavier and bigger that bad?\".\n\nWhile there is some truth to those rules, I'm pleasantly impressed that something like the Meteor 75 Pro, a considerably larger and heavier whoop that most would say is meant for outdoor flying, performed well in my indoor testing - both in a large open space and my room. And I think it's fascinating that I found myself wanting to go through more gaps despite the size increase. The increase in size may have also contributed to the 75 Pro's throttle control as I found throttle easy to manage. \n\nI did have a good amount of propwash when doing some tricks and brought this up to BetaFPV. I thought to myself \"Is heavier and bigger that bad?\".\n\nWhile there is some truth to those rules, I'm pleasantly impressed that something like the Meteor 75 Pro, a considerably larger and heavier whoop that most would say is meant for outdoor flying, performed well in my indoor testing - both in a large open space and my room. And I think it's fascinating that I found myself wanting to go through more gaps despite the size increase. The increase in size may have also contributed to the 75 Pro's throttle control as I found throttle easy to manage. \n\nI did have a good amount of propwash when doing some tricks and brought this up to BetaFPV.         </div>
        <ytd-text-inline-expander id="description-inline-expander" always-show-expand-button="" class="style-scope ytd-watch-metadata" show-expand-button=""><!--css-build:shady--><!--css-build:shady--><yt-attributed-string user-input="" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" hidden=""></yt-attributed-string><yt-formatted-string disable-attributed-string="" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" disable-upgrade="" hidden=""></yt-formatted-string><div id="snippet" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" style="overflow: hidden; max-height: 6rem; mask-image: linear-gradient(to top, transparent 0%, transparent 2rem, rgb(0, 0, 0) 2rem, rgb(0, 0, 0) 100%), linear-gradient(to right, rgb(0, 0, 0) 0%, rgb(0, 0, 0) 752px, transparent 776px, transparent 100%);"><span id="snippet-text" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander"><span id="plain-snippet-text" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" hidden=""></span><yt-attributed-string id="attributed-snippet-text" user-input="" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" dir="auto" role="text"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string--link-inherit-color" dir="auto" style="color: rgb(19, 19, 19);">I've been flying primarily 65 and 75 whoops for more than a year now and I've made a few rules for myself that I knew I should follow when building whoops: lightweight is key and smaller is easier to fly. However, with the release of the new Air75 and Air65, I was curious and wanted to see what the other end of the "whoop spectrum" was like. I thought to myself "Is heavier and bigger that bad?".</span></span></yt-attributed-string><yt-formatted-string id="formatted-snippet-text" disable-attributed-string="" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" disable-upgrade="" hidden=""></yt-formatted-string></span><span class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander">&nbsp;</span><span id="ellipsis" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander"></span><tp-yt-paper-button id="expand-sizer" class="button style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" style-target="host" role="button" tabindex="0" animated="" elevation="0" aria-disabled="false"><!--css-build:shady-->...more</tp-yt-paper-button></div><tp-yt-paper-button id="expand" class="button style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" style-target="host" role="button" tabindex="0" animated="" elevation="0" aria-disabled="false" style="left: 776px;"><!--css-build:shady-->...more</tp-yt-paper-button><div slot="extra-content" class="style-scope ytd-watch-metadata">
            <ytd-structured-description-content-renderer id="structured-description" inline-structured-description="" class="style-scope ytd-watch-metadata" modern="" hidden=""><!--css-build:shady--><!--css-build:shady--><div id="items" class="style-scope ytd-structured-description-content-renderer"><ytd-horizontal-card-list-renderer class="style-scope ytd-structured-description-content-renderer" at-start="" use-highlight-styling="" inline-structured-description="" card-list-style="HORIZONTAL_CARD_LIST_STYLE_TYPE_ENGAGEMENT_PANEL_SECTION" modern-chapters="" style="--ytd-horizontal-card-list-item-width: 0px;" can-show-more=""><!--css-build:shady--><!--css-build:shady--><div id="header-container" class="style-scope ytd-horizontal-card-list-renderer">

  <yt-formatted-string class="style-scope ytd-video-description-header-renderer">Wait this isn't the Air75? | Meteor 75 Pro Review</yt-formatted-string>

<div id="factoids" class="style-scope ytd-video-description-header-renderer"><factoid-renderer class="YtwFactoidRendererHost"><div class="YtwFactoidRendererFactoid" role="text" aria-label="214 likes"><span class="YtwFactoidRendererValue"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" role="text">214</span></span><span class="YtwFactoidRendererLabel"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" role="text">Likes</span></span></div></factoid-renderer><view-count-factoid-renderer><factoid-renderer class="YtwFactoidRendererHost"><div class="YtwFactoidRendererFactoid" role="text" aria-label="6,241 views"><span class="YtwFactoidRendererValue"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" role="text">6,241</span></span><span class="YtwFactoidRendererLabel"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" role="text">Views</span></span></div></factoid-renderer></view-count-factoid-renderer><factoid-renderer class="YtwFactoidRendererHost"><div class="YtwFactoidRendererFactoid" role="text" aria-label="Jul 27, 2024"><span class="YtwFactoidRendererValue"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" role="text">Jul 27</span></span><span class="YtwFactoidRendererLabel"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" role="text">2024</span></span></div></factoid-renderer></div>
</ytd-video-description-header-renderer><ytd-expandable-video-description-body-renderer class="style-scope ytd-structured-description-content-renderer" use-inline-expander="" engagement-panel=""><!--css-build:shady--><!--css-build:shady--><ytd-expander id="expander" class="style-scope ytd-expandable-video-description-body-renderer" hidden="" collapsed="" style="--ytd-expander-collapsed-height: 360px;"><!--css-build:shady--><!--css-build:shady--><div id="content" class="style-scope ytd-expander">
  
  <div id="description" slot="content" class="style-scope ytd-expandable-video-description-body-renderer">
    <yt-attributed-string class="content style-scope ytd-expandable-video-description-body-renderer" user-input=""><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" dir="auto"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string--link-inherit-color" dir="auto" style="color: rgb(19, 19, 19);">I've been flying primarily 65 and 75 whoops for more than a year now and I've made a few rules for myself that I knew I should follow when building whoops: lightweight is key and smaller is easier to fly. However, with the release of the new Air75 and Air65, I was curious and wanted to see what the other end of the "whoop spectrum" was like. I thought to myself "Is heavier and bigger that bad?".

While there is some truth to those rules, I'm pleasantly impressed that something like the Meteor 75 Pro, a considerably larger and heavier whoop that most would say is meant for outdoor flying, performed well in my indoor testing - both in a large open space and my room. And I think it's fascinating that I found myself wanting to go through more gaps despite the size increase. The increase in size may have also contributed to the 75 Pro's throttle control as I found throttle easy to manage. 

I did have a good amount of propwash when doing some tricks and brought this up to BetaFPV. After talking to several pilots, I was advised to check out UAVTech's video on the 75 Pro. I will be making some changes to mine but for the sake of this video, I wanted to present the Meteor 75 Pro with how others will get it. Future flight videos on my channel with the Meteor 75 Pro will have those changes.

Thank you again to </span><span class="yt-core-attributed-string--link-inherit-color" dir="auto" style="color: rgb(6, 95, 212);"><a class="yt-core-attributed-string__link yt-core-attributed-string__link--call-to-action-color" tabindex="0" href="/@BETAFPVHobby" target="" force-new-state="true">@BETAFPVHobby</a></span><span class="yt-core-attributed-string--link-inherit-color" dir="auto" style="color: rgb(19, 19, 19);"> for letting me review the Meteor 75 Pro. I'm very excited to get more flights with it very soon as it's honestly now part of my FPV bag. I'm also looking forward to the Air75 and Air65.

<ytd-text-inline-expander id="inline-expander" class="style-scope ytd-expandable-video-description-body-renderer" engagement-panel=""><!--css-build:shady--><!--css-build:shady--><yt-attributed-string user-input="" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" hidden=""></yt-attributed-string><yt-formatted-string disable-attributed-string="" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" disable-upgrade="" hidden=""></yt-formatted-string><div id="snippet" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" style="overflow: hidden; max-height: 36rem;"><span id="snippet-text" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander"><span id="plain-snippet-text" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander" hidden=""></span><yt-attributed-string id="attributed-snippet-text" user-input="" class="style-scope ytd-text-inline-expander"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string yt-core-attributed-string--white-space-pre-wrap" dir="auto"><span class="yt-core-attributed-string--link-inherit-color" dir="auto" style="color: rgb(19, 19, 19);">I've been flying primarily 65 and 75 whoops for more than a year now and I've made a few rules for myself that I knew I should follow when building whoops: lightweight is key and smaller is easier to fly. However, with the release of the new Air75 and Air65, I was curious and wanted to see what the other end of the "whoop spectrum" was like. I thought to myself "Is heavier and bigger that bad?".

While there is some truth to those rules, I'm pleasantly impressed that something like the Meteor 75 Pro, a considerably larger and heavier whoop that most would say is meant for outdoor flying, performed well in my indoor testing - both in a large open space and my room. And I think it's fascinating that I found myself wanting to go through more gaps despite the size increase. The increase in size may have also contributed to the 75 Pro's throttle control as I found throttle easy to manage. 

I did have a good amount of propwash when doing some tricks and brought this up to BetaFPV. After talking to several pilots, I was advised to check out UAVTech's video on the 75 Pro. I will be making some changes to mine but for the sake of this video, I wanted to present the Meteor 75 Pro with how others will get it. Future flight videos on my channel with the Meteor 75 Pro will have those changes.

Thank you again to </span><span class="yt-core-attributed-string--link-inherit-color" dir="auto" style="color: rgb(6, 95, 212);"><a class="yt-core-attributed-string__link yt-core-attributed-string__link--call-to-action-color" tabindex="0" href="/@BETAFPVHobby" target="" force-new-state="true">@BETAFPVHobby</a></span><span class="yt-core-attributed-string--link-inherit-color" dir="auto" style="color: rgb(19, 19, 19);"> for letting me review the Meteor 75 Pro. I'm very excited to get more flights with it very soon as it's honestly now part of my FPV bag. I'm also looking forward to the Air75 and Air65.

been flying primarily 65 and 75 whoops for more than a year now and I've made a few rules for myself that I knew I should follow when building whoops: lightweight is key and smaller is easier to fly. However, with the release of the new Air75 and Air65, I was curious and wanted to see what the other end of the \"whoop spectrum\" was like. I thought to myself \"Is heavier and bigger that bad?\".\n\nWhile there is some truth to those rules, I'm pleasantly impressed that something like the Meteor 75 Pro, a considerably larger and heavier whoop that most would say is meant for outdoor flying, performed well in my indoor testing - both in a large open space and my room. And I think it's fascinating that I found myself wanting to go through more gaps despite the size increase. The increase in size may have also contributed to the 75 Pro's throttle control as I found throttle easy to manage. \n\nI did have a good amount of propwash when doing some tricks and brought this up to BetaFPV. After talking to several pilots, I was advised to check out UAVTech's video on the 75 Pro. I will be making some changes to mine but for the sake of this video, I wanted to present the Meteor 75 Pro with how others will get it. I thought to myself \"Is heavier and bigger that bad?\".\n\nWhile there is some truth to those rules, I'm pleasantly impressed that something like the Meteor 75 Pro, a considerably larger and heavier whoop that most would say is meant for outdoor flying, performed well in my indoor testing - both in a large open space and my room. And I think it's fascinating that I found myself wanting to go through more gaps despite the size increase. The increase in size may have also contributed to the 75 Pro's throttle control as I found throttle easy to manage. \n\nI did have a good amount of propwash when doing some tricks and brought this up to BetaFPV. After talking to several pilots, I was advised to check out UAVTech's video on the 75 Pro. I will be making some changes to mine but for the sake of this video, I wanted to present the Meteor 75 Pro with how others will get it.
